  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Maria Weston Chapman writes that the Abolitionist newspaper must be put down, &quot;or it will put down the Mass. Soc.&quot; Therefore, it is necessary to send out agents for &quot;the cradle&quot; [the newspaper, the Cradle of Liberty], to counteract Amos A. Phelps&apos;s scheme of getting subscribers for the Abolitionist. Five hundred dollars are needed. Chapman considers a fair in New Bedford as a possible solution to the problem, and insists that Deborah Weston, along with Susan Taber, Mary Congdon, Mary Anna Bailey, etc., &quot;must get it up the 1st of June or so.&quot; The lectures of [William] Goodell could be sent all over the state by means of an effective agent.</subfield>
  </datafield>
